OBSOLETE Discussion and ideas around object ownership and locking in Zerolang.

These are old details discussions for archive purposes only.


#--: IDEA: error not to store reftypes returned

If a function returns a reftype, it should be an error to not store or
otherwise use (eg. by immediately calling a method on it) that reftype.

Reftypes take work to allocate on the heap and build... it is likely an error
not to use it at the call site. Or is a job for linter?

#--: Ownership rules

Rules for 'objects':

#ul:
  [#*: all objects have a single owner or parent which cannot be itself]
  [#*: ownership is to direct children only, it does not extend to grandchildren and
    there is no direct access to grandchildren]
  [#*: valtypes are copy by value. Each can only have a single owner, but easily
    copied so can make a new copy with a new owner.]
  [#*: reftypes are copy by reference. Can only have a single owner, but can be
    loaned via function calls or given away to a function call via a 'take'
    param]
  [#*: objects can only be disposed by their owner and no self-ownership so objects
    cannot dispose of themselves]
  [#*: all reftypes in object fields must be initialised and cannot be removed, only
    swapped]
  [#*: and, methods on reftype fields cannot be passed anything that is not owned
    (no borrowed references, eg self to prevent killing ourselves) Why not other
    borrowed references besides self?]
  [#*: ...so, reftypes in calls can only be borrowed (from parent call) or owned
    directly (local var). this.reftype???]
  [#*: returned reftypes always give ownership from function to caller. 'take' 
    arguments give ownership from caller to function (and are no longer valid at
    the caller from that point forward)]
  [#*: initialisation? The one true constructor must be called supplying all values,
    although default values can be used for valtypes.]
  [#*: destructor? There is a default destructor to recursively free all reftypes.
    Can be overridden to free/cleanup non-memory resources. Can return a single
    reftype from the class. How would that look?]

#--: TODO: enforcing correct #~"take" usage

Usage of 'take' enforced by the compiler.

Sometimes 'take' is required to notify the compiler of ownership transfer (eg
in parameter names).

In all other cases, the compiler MUST enforce that 'take' is only used on names
where the object is owned. eg. 

#ul:
  #*: NEVER on 'this'
  #*: NEVER on 'this' members. 
  #*: Allowed (?) on local vars (orig var is then inaccessible)
  #*: NEVER on for loops against iterators (these vars are borrowed)
  #*: optional on for loops against functions
  #*: can be used on 'cast' expressions as long as LHS is owned, forbidden otherwise

#--: Locking pseudocode

#code:
  start function env
    for each argument
      start arg env
      for each part
        if part exclusivelocked -> error
        share-lock part (can only get to children) What about function calls?


or just determine type for everything?

#ul:
  [#*: reference or value]
  [#*: ownership: owned, borrowed, this]
  [#*: constant or variable]
  [#*: lvalue (addressable) or rvalue (not addressable) (see also C++ categories:
    glvalue rvalue lvalue xvalue prvalue)]
  [#*: parent container (if any. eg in self.it, self is parent for it (for
    sharedlock))]
  [#*: owned component (eg, the component that is shadowed by this one while it is
    in scope. eg x: cast y as I --- x owns y while it is in scope)]

After processing all args in a call, then go through the resulting type of each
to do locking.

Locks:

#ul:
  [#*: sharedlock - no methods can be called on it. Child fields can be accessed
    (but not the child field that is exclusivelocked)]
  [#*: exclusivelock - ]
  [#*: none - like values?]

Procedure:

#ul:
  [#*: no locking for values (only for references)]
  [#*: no locking for top level references (data). These are readonly anyway, can be
    aliased]
  [#*: no locking for rvalues (anonymous references - eg returned from a function
    call) (generate an 'anonymous' name here to help with codegen?)]
  [#*: for lvalue references, each parent is sharedlocked and the final element is
    exclusivelocked]
  [#*: for owned references (casts) the destination is handled as a normal
    reference, the inner component is hidden (removed from current scope)]

Then check locking on the call/method itself, last.


#--: Attributes of expression result types:

These are all (mostly) orthogonal?

#---: Ownership:

#ul:
  [#*: immutable - top level (unit level) immutable type. The names of top level
    items are constant, cannot be redefined. Functions, #~"data", numeric types
    (although, these are passed by value so not a limitation that they are
    immutable)]
  [#*: free - (anonymous). Ownership is free to convey to the LHS/receiver. eg.
    return values from functions (not from iterators though); or all valtypes.
    An owned reftype variable can be converted to a free variable by using the
    #~"take" predefined type the the variable as the parameter. If ownership of a
    reftype is not taken by the LHS, the variable will be destroyed after the
    current statementline.]
  [#*: owned - var created locally or a "taken" parameter in a function body]
  [#*: borrowed - reftypes passed in via standard (non- #~"take") function parameter]
  [#*: linked - dotted member object of a composite type (eg record/class)]

Valtypes are always 'free' because they are always copied to new locations.

'linked' are dotted members of another parent variable (as with all vars, the
parent also is owned, borrowed or linked). This is a special class of ownership
(eg dotted members are not automatically owned just because you own the parent)
and have some additional restrictions (ie. they must be replaced if changed).

Items returned from function calls are always free.

immutable - yes/no (if yes, cannot be assigned to) - top level item usually

writeable - yes/no (if yes, can be assigned to) Could be no, but not immutable
eg an expression with no name

free - (anonymous) - yes/no (if yes, can be assigned from)



#---: Lock type:

All vars have a lock type. Unused local vars and parameters start with 'none'.

(For arguments at call sites; also 'cast', 'match', 'for' can lock target
object)

#ul:
  [#*: blocked - target of #~"match" (if not #~"take" -en), named (private members
    too?); local var definitions (including 'casts', eg. #~"newvar: object.protocol") 
    that take a non-'free' var on the RHS will take a lock while in scope. ]
  [#*: exclusive - a reftype directly passed into a call by name, or receiver in a
    method call]
  [#*: shared - a parent of a linked reftype passed into a call]
  [#*: none - for the 'free' ownership types: valtypes, result of function calls,
    unused local vars/arguments (?? what is that?)]

'blocked' makes the target totally unreferencable by that name. 

'exclusive' can have methods called on it but no reuse elsewhere and no child
access. All methods must take an exclusive lock on the receiver immediately
before the call.

'shared' will be for all parent items in a dotted chain except the last (which
will have an exclusive lock if it is a reftype field being passed); EXCEPT if
the final item is a valtype (in which case, there are no shared locks on the
parent items or the valtype)

'none' is essentially a noop for completeness; these situations have lock type
of 'none':

#ul:
  [#*: 'free' ownership types]
  [#*: as yet unreferenced vars]
  [#*: the results of function calls (they are 'free')]
  [#*: unit level items (because they are immutable (?)) - incl. functions, and
    unit level constant numbers and 'data'.]
  [#*: valtypes (they are free)... this includes the entire "path" up to that
    valtype - ie. no shared locks on parent components of a valtype reference]

The typesystem will check the locking of the parts of all calls. Multiple
shared locks on an object are ok, but only one exclusive lock on an object is
permitted. This includes the call (method) itself, which will need an exclusive
lock on the parent (if any).

After a call, all related locks are popped and cleared and the resulting object
is 'none'/'free' (except for iterators).

All locks take a reference to the location where the lock was taken for error
reporting purposes.

#---: Parameter flow type:

TODO: does statement context vs assignment context fit in this category? We
need to know if it is statement context for control flow 'statements' since
they have looser rules over return types (because there is no return type)

(What happens to this type provided as a call argument after that call)

#ul:
  #*: retained - ownership retained locally (at call site) after call
  #*: passed - ownership is given to the callee

Only 'owned' objects MAY be 'passed', all others are retained. To pass, the
parameter must retain ownership (ie. parameter must be a 'take' parameter),
otherwise, the argument will also be retained.
  
A 'passed' argument does not exist locally after the call. If it was 'named',
that name is no longer valid (blocked?). If it is 'linked', this is ILLEGAL
(subcomponents can only be changed with 'swap' (even if it is optional?))

For 'free' arguments: if 'passed' there is nothing to do; if 'retained'
then they are destroyed after the call (they can no longer be accessed since
they have no name)

#---: Ownership and Ownership movement

What is owned/not owned:

#ul:
  [#*: creating a protocol instance (object.protocolname), by default will be a
    borrowed object existing to the end of the current scope. The source name can
    be accessed again at the end of that scope.]
  [#*: creating a protocol instance from a taken object (take object.protocolname)
    creates an owned object that owns the source object. The source name can
    never be accessed again. XXX can't do this. Do protocol.create to make a
    'taken' protocol instance]

How to assign:

#ul:
  [#*: to assign to a field: source expression must be owned. Then use assignment
    (existing value before assignment will be destroyed) or #~"swap"]
  [#*: to use in a return expression: source expression must be owned]
  [#*: to call a function with #~"take" parameters: #~"take" must be used where the
    argument is specified and the source must be owned.]
  [#*: #~"take" may be used in #~"match" target variable and in #~"if" optional variable
    initialisation that want to take ownership of the item in the #~"then" clauses.
    (if not specified the item is borrowed)]

Note:

#ul:
  [#*: if an owned expression is not taken (by LHS (variable or field assignment) or
    call argument -> function parameter), it is automatically destroyed after use]
  [#*: using #~"take" on a variable that is not owned is an error]

#--: Ownership v3

#---: Attributes: type, ownership, mutability, lock

#----: Type

Type is an attribute of the object (not of the name).

- definition type (deftype) - top level object definition (record, class, enum,
  functions/methods, numeric constants, etc.) Compiler metadata only and are
  immutable.
- reference type (reftype) - has a runtime 'pointer'/'reference' to a type of
  possibly indeterminate size, has identity etc. Can only be created in
  run-time code.
- value type (valtype) - an inline block of data with a fixed size for this
  type. Has value semantics. Can be sources from some top level definitions
  (compile time numeric constants, function 'references'). Can only be created
  in run-time code.

#----: Ownership

Ownership is an attribute related to each expression in a function body.

- free: no name (anonymous); result of a standard call (except from a
  'borrowed' return as from an iterator); result of 'take' call; all valtypes
  are essentially 'free' to copy.
- owned: local owned var; #~"taken" reftype parameter
- borrowed: local borrowed var; non- #~"taken" reftype parameter; 'borrowed'
  return type of a function; result from an iterator; 'this' is always borrowed
- linked: child reftype field of an object 

linked....for returning borrowed, must be linked or borrowed (cannot be
  owned because it wont exist afterwards)

#----: Locality

Attribute related to the location of the object:

#ul:
  [#*: local - local variable in the current function scope. Variable will be
    destroyed when that scope ends. Includes:
    #ul:
      [#*: free (anonymous) objects]
      [#*: Local variables (owned variables; and shared variables that are bound to
        owned local vars)]
      [#*: 'taken' function parameters]
      [#*: (others?)]
    ]
  [#*: non-local - variable sourced from outside the current function scope that
    will live on after the function returns. Includes:
    #ul:
      [#*: non- 'taken' parameters (shared parameters)]
      [#*: linked variables; and shared vars bound to linked variables]
      [#*: (others?)]
    ]

Locality is passed in from the source. 'taken' variables become local but
otherwise a shared var will have the same locality as its source.


#----: Mutability

Mutability is an attribute related to the name of a 'variable'. The variable
value may still be mutable.

#ul:
  [#*: immutable - top level definitions; method names of object; 'this' inside an
    object]
  [#*: mutable - name can be copied to (with a compatible RHS, previous reftype
    value will be destroyed, valtypes will be copied over); or swapped]

#----: Lock

Lock type is an attribute related to each expression part in a function body.
Expressions 'hold' locks over other variable names/values. Only for reftypes;
valtypes and deftype always have a lock type of 'none'. When an expression is
assigned to a name, the expression locks are then carried with that name and
released when the name falls out of scope.

It is an error to attempt to take a lock that breaks the below rules:

#ul:
  [#*: exclusive - holder can do anything (call method, 'take' etc). No other
    expression can do anything with this expression while the lock is held. (ie.
    method calls, use as argument, reference children). No other lock of any type
    can be taken. Expression type must have a locktype of 'none' before an
    exclusive lock can be taken.]
  [#*: shared - can reference children, cannot call methods, cannot take an
    exclusive lock. Expression type must have a locktype of 'none' or other
    'shared' locks only before taking a shared lock.]
  [#*: none - no restrictions, can take a shared or exclusive lock. Top level
    definitions always have lock type of 'none' and take no locks on their RHS.
    Top level definitions are immutable and shareable - they are always deftypes
    or valtypes.]

#---: Operations

#----: createval

Create a new valtype variable. LHS must be a new label. RHS must be a valtype,
LHS becomes a copy of that value type.

#----: createref

Create a new reftype variable. LHS must be a new label. New variable will hold
all the locks that the RHS has taken.

RHS:

#ul:
  [#*: must be a reftype]
  [#*: RHS parents and 'leaf' must have lock type of 'none', else error]
  [#*: if free (use 'take' if required), LHS owns that expression. No locks.]
  [#*: if owned or borrowed, LHS borrows that expression and is given an exclusive
    lock to the RHS leaf and shared locks to all RHS parents until end of LHS's
    scope (the locks are transferred to the LHS name)]

#----: copyval

Only for valtypes. LHS must be owned (valtypes can never be borrowed or
linked). LHS name must be 'mutable'.

RHS must be assignable to the type of the LHS type (same type or losslessly
convertable to a larger numeric type in all cases).

#----: moveref

Only for reftypes. LHS must be owned or linked.

#ul:
  #*: RHS must be assignable to the LHS (the same type?)
  #*: RHS must be free or owned. Owned will be automatically promoted to free
  #*: if RHS is owned, its name will be destroyed after move
  #*: LHS prior value will be destroyed after move

#----: swapref

Only for reftypes. Both LHS and RHS must be:

#ul:
  #*: same type (exactly)
  #*: mutable variable names
  #*: owned (not borrowed)
  #*: must be able to take an exclusive lock on both immediately before the swap

#----: call (change this to 'locking'? Happens in all expressions)

A series of locking steps are done around a call.

#ul:
  #*: new lock frame added (?)
  #*: arguments processed left to right recursively (may involve a sub call)
  #*: shared lock taken on each parent
  #*: exclusive lock taken on each 'leaf' (final part of path)
  #*: 'loaned' returns ???


#----: take

#ul:
  #*: convert a 'mutable' name to a 'free' (unnamed) variable
  #*: variable must be 'owned'
  #*: can only 'take' local undotted variable names (no field member names)
  #*: the previous name is no longer available after the 'take'

#----: usage?

#ul:
  [#*: iterators - return loaned items]
  [#*: 'object.myprotocol' - returns a loaned item? Exclusively locks parent object.
    This item can be created on the stack since it will not outlive the current
    scope; no allocation is required.]
  [#*: 'myprotocol from: take object' - returns a new owned item. Can never get
    back to enclosed item]

#--: More thoughts on ownership/locking

For function returns:

#ul:
  [#*: take - (default) returns an owned object. Arguments are locked during the
    call but released when the object is returned. Caller is responsible for
    destroying returned object (this will happen when it falls out of scope)]
  [#*: borrow - returns a borrowed object. Arguments are locked during the call and
    remain in place until the returned object falls out of scope. Caller is NOT
    responsible for destroying returned object (it lives inside the associated
    object) A borrow return REQUIRES a lock on the parameter where the returned
    value lives]
  [#*: lock - N/A]

For parameters:

#ul:
  [#*: take - will take an exclusively owned object. It will no longer be valid in
    the caller]
  [#*: borrow - (default) will borrow the object. Cannot store or return it. Can
    only call methods on it]
  [#*: lock - will borrow the object, LOCKING it in the caller even after the call
    returns (lock is bound to the life of the returned object). Can store (in a
    new object only...) or return it. Can only call methods on it]

Inline (code):

#ul:
  [#*: take - will take an exclusively owned object. Target (if a named address)
    will no longer be valid going forward]
  [#*: borrow - (default) will borrow the object. Will lock the target]
  [#*: lock - same as borrow.]

In arguments:

same as 'Inline'. The specifier is optional and can be included to be
explicit/readable. But if the specifier is missing, the ownership type
specified in the function definition will still apply which may affect
availability of a named var after the call (for lock and take)

It is an error to explicitly provide an incompatible ownership/locking type.
eg. borrow arg, when the param is #~"take". Can this happen? if you #~"take arg" at
the call site for a locked arg, then the call site must keep a lock on the
anonymous var until the end of scope.


#--: Ownership v4

#---: ownership

#ul:
  #*: owned
  #*: borrowed

#---: locks

#ul:
  #*: none
  #*: exclusive
  #*: shared

#---: named

#ul:
  #*: named - associated with a name
  #*: anonymous - can be exclusively assigned (to a local var, to a taken argument)

#---: location

#ul:
  #*: local
  #*: nonlocal
  #*: shared


#--: From other notes

#code language=zerolang: """
  with x: in thing for x 



  for x: in thing loop {
  }

  with i: thing.each for x: i loop {
  }

  this
  self
  each

  """

For function returns:

#ul:
  [#*: 
    take - (default) returns an owned object. Arguments are locked during the
    call but released when the object is returned
    #ul:
      #*: Caller is responsible for destroying returned object (this will happen when
      it falls out of scope)
  ]
  [#*:
    borrow - returns a borrowed object. Arguments are locked during the call and
    remain in place until the returned object falls out of scope. 
    #ul:
      Caller is NOT responsible for destroying returned object (it lives inside
      the associated object) A borrow return REQUIRES a lock on the parameter where
      the returned value lives
  ]
  [#*: lock - N/A]

For parameters:

#ul:
  [#*: take - will take an exclusively owned object. It will no longer be valid in
    the caller]
  [#*: borrow - (default) will borrow the object. Cannot store or return it. Can
    only call methods on it]
  [#*: lock - will borrow the object, LOCKING it in the caller even after the call
    returns (lock is bound to the life of the returned object). Can store (in a
    new object only...) or return it. Can only call methods on it]

Inline (code):

#ul:
  [#*: take - will take an exclusively owned object. Target (if a named address)
    will no longer be valid going forward]
  [#*: borrow - (default) will borrow the object. Will lock the target]
  [#*: lock - same as borrow.]

In arguments:

same as 'Inline'. The specifier is optional and can be included to be
explicit/readable. But if the specifier is missing, the ownership type
specified in the function definition will still apply which may affect
availability of a named var after the call (for lock and take)

---

THINK: 'lock' should be on the object being locked instead of the returned
object? Requires returned object to be 'borrow'? This is more fine-grained
rather than locking all arguments... Yes, this is better and is more readable


#code language=zerolang: """
  myfunc: function {t: this} out this.borrow is { # error, borrow but no lock
    return t
  }

  myfunc: function {t: this.lock} out this.borrow is { # ok
    return t
  }

  myfunc: function {t: this.lock} out x is { # error? lock without a borrowed return? NO, no error. But x must be a reftype
    return # ...
  }
  """


#code language=zerolang: """
  myf1: function {t: this.lock} out this.borrow is {
    return t
  }

  myf2: function {t: this.lock} out this.borrow is {
    s: myf1 t	# will lock 't'
    return s	# can 'escape' because myf2 continues locking t ???
  }

  # no borrow, but still lock constrained

  myf1: function {t: this.lock} out this is {	# can't do this.. would need to be a borrow
    return t
  }

  myf2: function {t: this.lock} out this is {
    s: myf1 t	# will lock 't'
    return s	# can 'escape' because myf2 continues locking t ??? YES
  }

  myf3: function {t: this.lock} out this is {
    s: myf1 t	# will lock 't'
    s1: mysomethingelse	# owned, no locks
    if random {
            return s	# can 'escape' because myf2 continues locking t ???
    } else {
            return s1	# also allowed? The lock is unnecessary in this case but allowed?
    }
  }


  myf4: function {t: this.lock} out this is {
    s: myf1 t	# will lock 't'
    # s: myf1 lock t	# can explicitly show the lock is being taken?
    s1: mysomethingelse	# owned, no locks
    s3: if random {
            take s	# can 'escape' because myf4 continues locking t ???. (Note, we need to take. can we put the take before the 'if'? NO, take requires a typeref on RHS)
                    # BUT 's' is local... ?????
    } else {
            take s1	# also allowed? The lock is unnecessary in this case but allowed?
    }
    # both s and s1 are implied 'taken' at this point. The one that didn't get assigned to s3 it will be destroyed
    return s3	# the type of s3 requires locks because one of its options does? yes
  }
  """


take vs borrow:

take = caller must destroy; borrow = callee retains ownership and must eventually destroy (implies/requires(?) a lock)

#ul:
  [#*: this is part of the type and it is not compatible to assign to each other
    (taken v borrowed)]
  [#*: lock - return value holds a lock over these parameters. return value may not
    escape to an area where this lock is not held]
  [#*: both taken and borrowed return values can lock items]
  [#*: error to take a lock if the return is a valtype or none ?]
  [#*: error to explicitly 'take' when providing an argument to a borrowed parameter
    (but still need to handle this eg. when the result of a call is passed to a
    function)]
  [#*: locks can also be held by object instances over their constructor arguments
    (of course: these are handled the same as normal func/method calls)]
  [#*: locks must be on a location (ie. not on a 'free' / anonymous var such as the
    result of a standard function call)]
  [#*: locks are temporary (assigned by the compiler for a call only) or permanent,
    assigned to the life of the return value so must be explicitly specified by
    user with 'lock' keyword]
  [#*: temporary locks can be shared or exclusive]
  [#*: permanent locks are always exclusive (?). Nothing can be done in the
    containing scope (no calls, can't be passed as args, returned etc)]


lock:

#ul:
  [#*: 'anonymous' (/taken) expressions have 0 locks]
  [#*: 'owned' (single reference) has 1 exclusive lock]
  [#*: 'take' can only be done on an owned reference with no other locks on it]
  [#*: an expression can have only 1 (or none) exclusive locks]
  [#*: an expression can have multiple shared locks from multiple expressions]
  [#*: must take an exclusive lock on an item before calling any methods on it]
  [#*: 
    a borrow is a borrowed reference with locks over the RHS (shared on all
    parent parts of the RHS, and exclusive on the final part)

    #ul:
      [#*: (can borrow an anonymous expression? no, can't specify borrow as a keyword
      here)]
      [#*: a borrowed parameter also has a lock over the passed in argument.]
  ]
  [#*: 
    for a function return, if the returned item holds any locks, the function
    must also lock those items 
    #ul:
      #*: (the returned item must be returned into an equivalently locked environment)
  ]
  [#*: 
    for a function returning an owned item (default), the item being returned
    must be owned 
          
    #ul:
      #*: (but may be locked if the function itself has similar locks)
  ]
  [#*: 
    for a function returning a borrowed item, the item being returned must be
    also borrowed or shared
    #ul:
      [#*: this is because the item needs to 'live' somewhere that will take care of
      eventual destruction]
      [#*: borrowed items always have locks, so the function itself must have similar
      locks.]
      [#*: this includes the locks over passed in arguments - if you are returning one
      of these, the function must maintain the lock over that argument]
  ]
  [#*: 
    all locks on local items are dropped and local values are destroyed
    immediately before a 'return' statement 
    #ul:
      [#*: (except the item itself being returned)]
      [#*: so if there is a lock on an item by a local item, you will be allowed to
      return that? this is too complicated?]
  ]

lock implementation:

#ul:
  #*: locks are maintained using two way lockup? So you can see what locks are held
