#ul:
  [#*: #~"take", #~"borrow" and #~"lock" (anything defined on a variable name) cannot be
    an actual type at #~"system.*" -- they are type modifiers in the type system
    only, so only available as a 'method'/attribute on the variable name or on
    the type name.]
  [#*: make #~"borrow" and #~"limit" the same? Remove #~"limit" and use #~"borrow" in all
    cases?]
  [#*: make #~"borrow" and #~"lock" be namespaces that hold all interfaces supported by
    this object? Then:
    #ul:
      [#*: #~"myobject.borrow.myprotocol" when used as a type specifier or on a named var
         creates/requires a borrowed reference can *only* access the methods/fields
         specified in #~"myprotocol". In arguments, the passed type will automatically
         convert to the limited type provided the caller has equal or higher access
         rights to the instance (ie. has an owned reference or a limited reference that
         includes access to the specified protocol. Can be specified in expressions,
         parameter types (but, this is the default for args), localvars and return
         types.]
      [#*: #~"myobject.borrow" is equivalent to #~"myobject.borrow.public" and creates a
         borrowed reference that can access the entire public interface of #~"myobject"]
      [#*: #~"myobject.borrow.private" when specified as a parameter type allows access to
         the private namespace of #~"myobject". *Only* the internal methods of #~"myobject"
         itself can call a function that requires the private namespace. #~"private"
         cannot be specified in local vars or return types.]
      [#*: #~"myobject.lock.myprotocol" when used as a parameter type can only access the
         methods/fields specified in #~"myprotocol". After returning from the function,
         #~"myobject" will be locked, bound to the lifetime of the returned limited
         object. Note that regardless of which subprotocol is specified, the *entire*
         object is locked in the caller. #~"lock" cannot be used in return types or local
         vars.]
      [#*: #~"myobject.lock" is equivalent to #~"myobject.lock.public".]
      [#*: #~"myobject.lock.private" when specified as a parameter type allows access to
         the private namespace of #~"myobject" and then locks the instance in the caller,
         bound to the life of the returned limited object. *Only* the internal methods
         of #~"myobject" itself can call a function that requires the private namespace.
         #~"private" cannot be specified in local vars or return types.]
    ]


Details (fix these):

#ul:
  [#*: #~"take" 
    #ul:
      [#*: is a predefined type at #~"system.take" (? no)]
      [#*: is a predefined 'call' on a variable *_name_* (but is a no-op on valtypes)]
      [#*: is a predefined (compiler defined) (sub-) type specifier on all types (but
      is a no-op on valtypes ie. same as the parent type because valtypes are always
      owned)]
      [#*: if the parent type is generic, then the #~"take" subtype also has the same
      generic parameters]
  ]
  [#*: #~"borrow" is a predefined type at #~"system.borrow". Also a predefined 'call' on
    a variable #_*"name". And a predefined (compiler defined) type specifier on all
    reftypes. If the parent type is generic, then the #~"borrow" subtype also has
    the same generic parameters.]
  [#*: #~"lock" is a predefined type at #~"system.lock". Also a predefined 'call' on
    a variable #_*"name". And a predefined (compiler defined) type specifier on all
    reftypes. If the parent type is generic, then the #~"lock" subtype also has the
    same generic parameters.]
  [#*: #~"generic" is a predefined type at #~"system.generic". Also a predefined 'call'
    on item definitions of #~"union", #~"variant", #~"protocol" and #~"facet" (only) that
    will define a generic field or parameter in a type specification only
    (constant only, not usable at runtime). If the parent type is generic, then
    this #~"generic" subtype also has the same generic parameters.]
  [#*: #~"tag" is a predefined type at #~"system.tag". Also a predefined type on the
    base numeric types that can be used as a tag (#~"u8" #~"u16" #~"u32" #~"u64" #~"u128"
    #~"i8" #~"i16" #~"i32" #~"i64" #~"i128" #~"c8" #~"c32"). When using the base numeric types,
    the descriminators do not need to be complete (specified for all values of
    that type). Tags are also given a name in sum type definitions. If public,
    these can be referred to in other type definitions and in this case, the
    definition in that new type must be complete (ie. a definition given for
    every value provided in the source tag)]
  [#*: #~"typedef" is a predefined type at #~"system.typedef". Also a predefined 'call'
    on all item definitions (including builtins). If the parent type is generic,
    then this #~"typedef" subtype also has the same generic parameters. TODO: not
    needed anymore since we can directly specify a typedef'd type in an #~"is"
    operation of item declarations.]

#code language=zerolang: """
  myfunc: function {t: this.lock} out this.borrow is { # ok (and not a constructor)
    return t
  }
  """

#---: locking and escaping with a lock

#code language=zerolang: """
  # OK - y is borrowed over a lock on x
  # (but cannot be returned as a borrow because it is a localvar)
  y: x.borrow

  # OK - z is borrowed over a lock on y (which maintains the lock over x)
  z: y.borrow

  # OK - a (z.childref) is borrowed over a lock on the *parent* (z)
  a: z.childref.borrow

  # borrow is the default so does not have to be specified
  """

#code language=zerolang: """
  # NOT allowed. cannot return a borrow without a lock
  myfunc: function {t: reftype} out reftype.borrow is {
    return t
  }
  """

#code language=zerolang: """
  # NOT allowed. cannot return a borrow without a lock
  # cannot return a local var as a borrow (it must live somewhere)
  myfunc: function out reftype.borrow is {
    t: reftype
    return t
  }
  """

#code language=zerolang: """
  # OK - the borrow is over the locked item
  myfunc: function {t: reftype.lock} out reftype.borrow is {
    return t
  }
  """

#code language=zerolang: """
  # NOT allowed - cannot borrow local var and there is no lock over 
  #   the returned type
  myfunc: function {t: reftype.lock} out reftype.borrow is {
    t: makereftype
    return t
  }
  """

#code language=zerolang: """
  # NOT allowed. cannot return a borrow without a lock
  myfunc: function {t: this} out reftype.borrow is {
    return t.myreftype
  }
  """

#code language=zerolang: """
  # OK - locking parent locks all chidren
  myfunc: function {t: this.lock} out reftype.borrow is {
    return t.myreftype
  }
  """

#code language=zerolang: """
  mycall: function {t: reftype.lock} out refchild.borrow is {
    return t.myrefchild
  }

  # OK - locking is maintained in caller
  myfunc: function {t: reftype.lock} out refchild.borrow is {
    x: mycall t # x is borrowed over a lock on t
    return x  # ok, x is escaping into an env that also locks t
  }
  """
